column30: The coding experience at ITP is so specific. Since I’m new to coding I want to know more what it’s like in the real world. And to be prepared and have some social tools to deal with people challenges.

In my experience, there isn’t a single monolithic coding community, but rather a variety of different communities that each have their own norms. Some are welcoming and beginner-friendly (e.g. ITP or the Recurse Center), while others are not (e.g. StackOverflow).

column2: on and off for 2 years, but always in my free time and never getting past a certain point
column30: it is much easier to learn to code when you are in a physical community full of other beginners. otherwise it is so easy to get discouraged when you hit a certain level of frustration. i've tried online courses and it's just so hard to follow through on my own. the community + structure of a classroom with homework is helpful (for me at least)

column34: Began learning HTML when I was 8 years old in 2001. Started a bit of interactive programming with Applescript when I was 13 in 2006, and I really wish someone had pushed me to dive deeper into programming at that point. I didn't really get into it enough to make anything useful until college. I did a web development bootcamp at GA after college graduation which was helpful although I could probably have learned it all on my own.

column30: I enjoy coding and problem solving, but I did not enjoy some the experiences I had with people in developer community. I wish I could say those people and experiences didn't affect or deter me, but they did. I felt very conflicted about having a career in tech because of that. After coming to ITP, I am glad I've met people who value making different things. I will make the thing I believe in and stand my ground in tech.
